paragraphs.text: %md ## OML Third-Party Packages - R Environment Usage Oracle Machine Learning Notebooks provides a conda interpreter to install third-party Python and R packages in a conda environment for use within OML Notebooks sessions, as well as within OML4R and OML4Py embedded execution invocations. Conda is an open source package and environment management system that enables the use of virtual environments containing third-party R and Python packages. With conda environments, you can install and update packages and their dependencies, as well as switch between environments to use project-specific packages. Administrators create conda environments and install packages that can then be accessed by non-administrator users and loaded into their OML Notebooks session and used in embedded execution using the native language, SQL, and REST APIs. In the template notebook titled *OML Third-Party Packages - Environment Creation*, the ADMIN user creates a conda environment, installs packages, and uploads the conda environments to Object Storage. In this notebook, we demonstrate a typical workflow for conda environment usage in OML Notebooks using R and OML4R. The OML user downloads and uses the packages in conda environments that were previously created and saved to an Object Storage bucket folder associated with the Autonomous Database. --- Copyright (c) 2022 Oracle Corporation ###### The Universal Permissive License (UPL), Version 1.0 ---

msg.data:
OML Third-Party Packages - R Environment Usage

Oracle Machine Learning Notebooks provides a conda interpreter to install third-party Python and R packages in a conda environment for use within OML Notebooks sessions, as well as within OML4R and OML4Py embedded execution invocations. Conda is an open source package and environment management system that enables the use of virtual environments containing third-party R and Python packages. With conda environments, you can install and update packages and their dependencies, as well as switch between environments to use project-specific packages.

Administrators create conda environments and install packages that can then be accessed by non-administrator users and loaded into their OML Notebooks session and used in embedded execution using the native language, SQL, and REST APIs.

In the template notebook titled OML Third-Party Packages - Environment Creation, the ADMIN user creates a conda environment, installs packages, and uploads the conda environments to Object Storage.

In this notebook, we demonstrate a typical workflow for conda environment usage in OML Notebooks using R and OML4R. The OML user downloads and uses the packages in conda environments that were previously created and saved to an Object Storage bucket folder associated with the Autonomous Database.

Copyright (c) 2022 Oracle Corporation

The Universal Permissive License (UPL), Version 1.0

paragraphs.title: List all environments saved in Object Storage
paragraphs.text:
%conda

list-saved-envs

paragraphs.title: List a named environment in Object Storage
paragraphs.text:
%md
---
Use `list-saved-envs` to list and return the details for a named conda environment in Object Storage.  The environment name, size, and number of packages is returned along with the description and tags provided by the ADMIN when uploading the environment.

The application tag indicates how the environment can be used.  For example, the environment `myrenv` was created with the application tag *OML4R* for use with R and OML4R.

msg.data:
Use list-saved-envs to list and return the details for a named conda environment in Object Storage. The environment name, size, and number of packages is returned along with the description and tags provided by the ADMIN when uploading the environment.

The application tag indicates how the environment can be used. For example, the environment myrenv was created with the application tag OML4R for use with R and OML4R.

paragraphs.text:
%conda

list-saved-envs -e myrenv

%md
---
## Using an R environment
---

In this example, we predict the number of international passengers traveling by airplane using time series data. The R packages used are *forecast* and *ggplot2* with the conda environment *myrenv*. We first run the code and create a UDF using R, followed by invoking the UDF in OML4R embedded R execution from the R, SQL and REST APIs.

msg.data:
Using an R environment

In this example, we predict the number of international passengers traveling by airplane using time series data. The R packages used are forecast and ggplot2 with the conda environment myrenv. We first run the code and create a UDF using R, followed by invoking the UDF in OML4R embedded R execution from the R, SQL and REST APIs.

paragraphs.title: Download and activate the environment
paragraphs.text:
%md
---
Conda environments are available after they are downloaded and activated using the `download` and `activate` functions in a %conda paragraph. An activated environment is available until it is deactivated.

msg.data: Conda environments are available after they are downloaded and activated using the download and activate functions in a %conda paragraph. An activated environment is available until it is deactivated.

paragraphs.title: Download and activate the 'myrenv' environment
paragraphs.text:
%conda

download myrenv

activate myrenv

paragraphs.title: Load libraries and suppress warnings
paragraphs.text:
%r

library(ggplot2)
library(forecast)

options(warn=-1)
options(ore.warn.order=FALSE)

paragraphs.title: Load and prepare data
paragraphs.text:
%r

data("AirPassengers")

# Through the end of 1956, no months in 1957
air.train <- window(AirPassengers, end = 1956+11/12)

# everything in 1957 and beyond
air.test  <- window(AirPassengers, start = 1957)

n.test <- length(air.test)

paragraphs.title: Fit an arima model to the data and compute performance
paragraphs.text:
%r

air.model <- auto.arima(air.train)

paragraphs.title: Create multi-step forecasts for each day
paragraphs.text:
%r

accuracy(air.model)

air.multi.forecast <- air.model %>% forecast(h = n.test)

air.multi.forecast %>% autoplot()

accuracy(air.multi.forecast, x = air.test)

air.multi.forecast %>%
  autoplot() +
  geom_line(
    aes(
      x = as.numeric(time(air.test)),
      y = as.numeric(air.test)
    ),
    col = "red"
  )

paragraphs.title: Create R UDF
paragraphs.text:
%r

multi.forecast <- function() {
	library(forecast)
	library(ggplot2)
	data("AirPassengers")
    air.train <- window(AirPassengers, end = 1956+11/12)
    air.test  <- window(AirPassengers, start = 1957)
    n.test <- length(air.test)
	air.model <- auto.arima(air.train)
	accuracy(air.model)
	air.multi.forecast <- air.model %>% forecast(h = n.test)
	air.multi.forecast %>% autoplot()
	res <- accuracy(air.multi.forecast, x = air.test)
	print(air.multi.forecast %>%
		autoplot() + geom_line(
		aes(x = as.numeric(time(air.test)), y = as.numeric(air.test)), col = "red"))
	return(res)}

paragraphs.title: Run the UDF in R
paragraphs.text:
%r

multi.forecast()

paragraphs.text:
%md

---
### Running UDFs in the SQL and REST APIs for embedded R execution
---
To use the SQL and REST APIs for embedded R execution, the UDF function must be stored in the script repository, and an Oracle Machine Learning (OML) cloud account USERNAME, PASSWORD, and URL must be provided to obtain an authentication token. To use a conda environment when calling OML4R script execution endpoints, specify the conda environment in the `env_name` field when using SQL, and the `envName` field when using REST.

Obtain the token URL from the OML service console in Autonomous Database by first signing into your Oracle Cloud Infrastructure account with your OCI user name and password:

- Click the “three line menu” and select the desired Autonomous Database instance.
- Click Database Actions and scroll down to the Oracle Machine Learning RESTful Services tile.
- Click “Copy” to get the REST authentication token for REST APIs URL of the form: /omlusers/api/oauth2/v1/token

The includes the location, tenancy ID, and database name separated by dashes. For example, https://qtraya2braestch-omldb.adb.us-sanjose-1.oraclecloudapps.com.

Running UDFs in the SQL and REST APIs for embedded R execution

To use the SQL and REST APIs for embedded R execution, the UDF function must be stored in the script repository, and an Oracle Machine Learning (OML) cloud account USERNAME, PASSWORD, and URL must be provided to obtain an authentication token. To use a conda environment when calling OML4R script execution endpoints, specify the conda environment in the env_name field when using SQL, and the envName field when using REST.

Obtain the token URL from the OML service console in Autonomous Database by first signing into your Oracle Cloud Infrastructure account with your OCI user name and password:

  • Click the “three line menu” and select the desired Autonomous Database instance.
  • Click Database Actions and scroll down to the Oracle Machine Learning RESTful Services tile.
  • Click “Copy” to get the REST authentication token for REST APIs URL of the form: /omlusers/api/oauth2/v1/token

The includes the location, tenancy ID, and database name separated by dashes. For example, https://qtraya2braestch-omldb.adb.us-sanjose-1.oraclecloudapps.com.

paragraphs.title: Create access details table to support token acquisition
Obtain an authentication token
Add the OML user to the Access Control List
paragraphs.text:
%md
---
The Access Control List (ACL) provides additional protection to your Autonomous Database by allowing only the client with specific IP addresses to connect to the database. 

As ADMIN user in SQL Developer, use the network access control lists `rqAppendHostAce` function to enable the OML user to access network services and resources from the database, where the root domain is the data center region where Autonomous Database resides, e.g. *adb.us-region-1.oraclecloudapps.com*. 

Then run the token store function `rqSetAuthToken` to persist the authorization token issued by a cloud host for use with the upcoming SQL calls.

msg.data:
The Access Control List (ACL) provides additional protection to your Autonomous Database by allowing only the client with specific IP addresses to connect to the database.

As ADMIN user in SQL Developer, use the network access control lists rqAppendHostAce function to enable the OML user to access network services and resources from the database, where the root domain is the data center region where Autonomous Database resides, e.g. adb.us-region-1.oraclecloudapps.com.

Then run the token store function rqSetAuthToken to persist the authorization token issued by a cloud host for use with the upcoming SQL calls.

paragraphs.title: Show the list of available OML4R conda environments
paragraphs.text:
%script

set long 1000

select * from table(rqListEnvs())

paragraphs.title: Run the R UDF using the SQL API for embedded R execution
paragraphs.text:
%script

SELECT name, id, value, dbms_lob.substr(image,100,1) image FROM table(rqEval2( 
    par_lst => '{"ore_graphics_flag":true}', 
    out_fmt => 'PNG', 
    scr_owner=> NULL,
    scr_name => 'multi.forecast',
    env_name => 'myrenv'));

paragraphs.title: Run the R UDF using the REST API for embedded R execution in synchronous mode
paragraphs.text:
$ curl -i -X POST --header "Authorization: Bearer ${token}" --header 'Content-Type: application/json' 
       --header 'Accept: application/json' -d '{"input":"DF", "envName":"myrenv", "graphicsFlag":true}' 
       "${omlserver}/oml/api/r-scripts/v1/do-eval/multi.forecast"

%md
